<br>
She looked up into her reflection.  How could Aeli possibly even have the heart to look at her?  Of course, he lived almost in ignorance.  He did not know the Sirens were often called angels of death.  Doxies, lily whores, anything the humans could have managed to make up.  He didn't know the ways the humans tormented them...and established their position over them.<br>
<br>
He would never know, as long as she had a say.<br>
<br>
Her eyes traveled to the ankh around her neck.  A beautiful thing, solid gold, tied to a thin, silver chain.  Come to think of it, she had no idea where she had gotten it, or how it had come to be on her neck, only that she had had it for as long as she remembered.<br>
<br>
And she couldn't remember anything before age six.<br>
<br>
It had subtle powers...transferring energy between her and others, sickly people she had met on her journey.  But otherwise, it had no use but to look pretty.  Right now, Laurena looked upon it with scorn, remembering Tryphaena's words...<br>
<br>
Brings back old memories...Wouldn't you love to know...<br>
<br>
And Tryphaena had one too, a black onyx one, with an identical silver chain.  Only hers gave death.<br>
<br>
Suddenly afraid of the thing, she tried to take it off.  It wouldn't fit over her head, though, and had no clasp! Sighing in frustration, she tried to break the chain, wishing suddenly to be rid of the blasted thing.<br>
<br>
(NO!)<br>
<br>
Suddenly Laurena was struck frozen by the sound of dying screams and maniacal laughter...the room melted away into perverted night, and flames rose over her head and surrounded her.  She was in a village, and it was night.<br>
<br>
Figures dashed through the night, screaming.  Larger figures with swords and club ran about, slaying the winged ones.  A few took off into the sky, desperate to escape the slaughter, but were shot down by arrows...They were setting fire to the huts...<br>
<br>
A certain series of screams caught her attention. Humans dragged out a woman siren from the hut right beside her, writhing and screaming her deathsong in agony as they violated her cruelly to her end.  Then, they retreated back into the crude house and dragged out a little one by the wrists and legs, throwing her onto the ground. Blood marked the spot where the little siren fell.  She screamed as they beat her to death with clubs and ripped her of her wings, and her deathsong pierced the night.<br>
<br>
Laurena could not tear her gaze away from this.  Her heart had completely stopped, her breath no more.  Horror coursed through her.  But she was able to  look away, to see another figure who walked out of the now burning hut. <br>
<br>
It was a siren, but unlike the others, she walked freely and without fear.  She was little too, only a little older than the one who now laid dead and mangled at her feet.  The little one looked down at the dead child, and tossed her raven haired head back in laughter.<br>
<br>
Her wings were black.<br>
<br>
She stepped over the corpse without a second glance, and movd onward into the flaming, screaming night.<br>
<br>
Laurena suddenly was close to the body of the dead siren, and was forced to look down at the face, whose eyes...whose amethyst eyes...were wide and glazed in bitter death, and whose chestnut hair was matted in blood.<br>
<br>
Laurena screamed.<br>
********<br>
<br>
Azalea awoke briefly, feelign very refreshed.  &quot;Laurena? Did you not get any sleep at all?&quot;<br>
<br>
She looked at her.  She was standing in front of the mirror, dead still, her ankh clutched in her hand.  The hand was trembling, and her breath was not to be heard.<br>
<br>
&quot;Laurena?  Are you all...&quot;<br>
<br>
Her words were cut off by a long ear-piercing scream that emanated from Laurena's slackened lips, a scream of complete and uninhibited horror.  And then, as sudden as she had started, she stopped, seeming to return to the present world.  Gasping, she collapsed to the floor, trying to grasp something as she fell and knocking over several items on the vanity table with a clatter.<br>
<br>
&quot;Laurena!&quot; Azalea jumped up and rushed to her side.  &quot;Laurena, speak to me.  What happened? What did you see? Laurena!&quot;<br>
<br>
The black mage reacted quickly.  She laid the siren in the bed nearby and covered her up tightly, putting spells on her wrists and ankles so she wouldn't hurt herself.  Then, with some thought, she cast a sleeping spell on the woman, whose eyes had been wide in unspeakable terror, now fluttered shut in spell induced slumber.<br>
<br>
Azalea looked towards the door, hoping no one had heard her.  &quot;Tryphaena, you cunning bitch of birds...&quot; she whispered to herself.  <br>
